<paragraph id="E8403669FF81FFFCFF591C328767B2E6" blockId="22.[160,1155,1599,1728]" lastBlockId="23.[160,1155,142,237]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="822" pageId="22" pageNumber="821">
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF81FFFDFF591C328426B453" author="Donnelly N" box="[192,370,1599,1624]" pageId="22" pageNumber="821" pagination="7 - 9" refId="ref24517" refString="Donnelly N. 2002. Odonata of St. Thomas and St. John, Virgin Islands. Argia. 14 (1): 7 - 9." type="journal article" year="2002">Donnelly (2002)</bibRefCitation>
only states: ‘On a few ponds; not common.’ Presumably, he meant on St. Thomas. We found adults and nymphs of this species only at two sites: Dorothea turtle pond on St. Thomas, and an ornamental water garden on Water Island. Both sites are on hill tops, well above 700 metres asl, with dense surrounding tree cover. Known commonly as the ‘tawny pennant’ across some Caribbean islands, other surveys also note very localised distributions, even when abundant (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFD351ABC86C0B2C1" author="Meurgey F &amp; David G &amp; Thiebaut B" box="[684,916,177,202]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="14 - 16" refId="ref27267" refString="Meurgey F, David G, Thiebaut B. 2008. 2008 Collecting trip in Martinique (French West Indies). Argia. 20 (2): 14 - 16." type="journal article" year="2008">Meurgey et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFC3A1ABC8583B2E6" author="Catling PM &amp; Kostiuk B" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="20 - 24" refId="ref23381" refString="Catling PM, Kostiuk B. 2015. A dry season survey of the dragonflies of St. Kitts and Nevis, Northeastern Leeward Islands. Argia. 27 (3): 20 - 24." type="journal article" year="2015">Catling and Kostiuk 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFF7D1AD98772B2E6" author="Trapero-Quintana A &amp; Torres-Cambas Y &amp; Rivas-Torres A &amp; Ferreira S &amp; Cordero-Rivera A" box="[228,550,212,237]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="15 - 28" refId="ref30988" refString="Trapero-Quintana A, Torres-Cambas Y, Rivas-Torres A, Ferreira S, Cordero-Rivera A. 2020. The Odonata of Zapata peninsula (Matanzas, Cuba), the largest wetland system of the Caribbean. Odonatologica. 49: 15 - 28." type="journal article" year="2020">Trapero-Quintana et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
